Part I - (Ford Gobike Data Exploration)¶

by Rawan Alsaedi¶

Introduction¶

This project has two parts that demonstrate the importance and value of data visualization techniques in the data analysis process.

In Part I, Exploratory data visualization, you will use Python visualization libraries to systematically explore a selected dataset, starting from plots of single variables and building up to plots of multiple variables. In Part II, Explanatory data visualization, you will produce a short presentation that illustrates interesting properties, trends, and relationships that you discovered in your selected dataset. The primary method of conveying your findings will be through transforming your exploratory visualizations from the first part into polished, explanatory visualizations.

Ford Gobike Dataset¶

This dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

#Plot the distribution of Age
def plot_age(data,y , title):
    sb.boxplot(data=data ,y=y , color ="b")
    plt.xticks(rotation=15);
    plt.title(title , fontsize=15);
plot_age(data=df_ford ,y="age" , title="Distribution of Age") ;

15.What is distribution of trips by gender , bikeshare , weekday and user type ?¶

# plot bar to show the relationship between trips & gender , bikeshare , weekday and user type
def trip_factors():
    Factors = ['member_gender', 'bike_share_for_all_trip', 'weekday_st']
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=[14.70, 8.27])
    for i, s in enumerate(Factors):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(3, 3, i+1)
        plt.title('Distribution of Bike Trips'); 
        plt.ylabel('Count');
        df_ford.groupby([s, 'user_type'])[s].count().unstack('user_type').plot(ax=ax, kind='bar', stacked=True )
        plt.tight_layout() 

trip_factors()

- Male took around %80 of all bike rides.¶

- Most bike rides users are Subscriber .¶

- Most bike rides users didn't sharing bike for all trips.¶

- Thursday has the highest number of bike rides trips.¶
